            <h2 class="title tir is-2 is-size-4-mobile m-4">
                Introducing The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines<br>(WCAG&nbsp;-&nbsp;"Wu-Kag")
            </h2>


            <p class="tir is-size-5-mobile m-4">
                Wikipedia has a great description: "The&nbsp;<strong>Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>WCAG</strong>) are part of a series of&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_accessibility">web accessibility</a>&nbsp;guidelines published by the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Accessibility_Initiative">Web Accessibility Initiative</a>&nbsp;(WAI) of the&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web_Consortium">World Wide Web Consortium</a>&nbsp;(W3C), the main international standards organization for the Internet. They are a set of recommendations for making Web content more accessible, primarily for people with&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disabilities">disabilities</a>—but also for all&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_agent">user agents</a>, including highly limited devices, such as mobile phones. WCAG 2.0, was published in December 2008 and became an&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardization">ISO</a>&nbsp;standard, ISO/IEC 40500:2012 in October 2012. WCAG 2.1 became a W3C Recommendation in June 2018." WCAG 2.2 is still in Draft at this time.

            </p>


            <p class="tir is-size-5-mobile m-4">
                But what does that all mean? Well, going back to my color blind story from before: In the chart article we see that it points to <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#non-text-content">1.1.1 Non-text Content</a> and <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG21/#use-of-color">1.4.1 Use of Color</a>. Both of these sections tell you how to address a chart (1.1.1) and how to treat color in general (1.4.1). As you dig into this more, you start to see how much can go into accessibility.

            </p>
